00:03:12.647 --> 00:03:13.480
Let's start in here.

00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:17.560
I want to know if anybody here
knows who these two people are.

00:03:17.560 --> 00:03:20.250
Anybody know who this
person is on the right?

00:03:20.250 --> 00:03:20.820
Tell me.

00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:21.500
Who is it?

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:22.354
AUDIENCE: John Ive.

00:03:22.354 --> 00:03:23.270
PROFESSOR: Johnny Ive.

00:03:23.270 --> 00:03:23.770
Absolutely.

00:03:23.770 --> 00:03:25.262
And what does Johnny Ive do?

00:03:25.262 --> 00:03:28.775
AUDIENCE: He's the
Chief Designer at Apple.

00:03:28.775 --> 00:03:29.400
PROFESSOR: Yup.

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:31.560
Chief Designer at Apple
for hardware products.

00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:32.540
AUDIENCE: Industrial Designer.

00:03:32.540 --> 00:03:32.980
PROFESSOR: Industrial Designer.

00:03:32.980 --> 00:03:33.960
Exactly.

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:37.120
And on the left-- this guy
here in the black and white

00:03:37.120 --> 00:03:41.590
picture-- who's he?

00:03:41.590 --> 00:03:42.399
Hah.

00:03:42.399 --> 00:03:43.940
Not as famous as
Johnny Ive, I guess.

00:03:43.940 --> 00:03:44.750
Oh, maybe he is.

00:03:44.750 --> 00:03:45.587
Hold on.

00:03:45.587 --> 00:03:46.840
AUDIENCE: Is it Dieter Rams?

00:03:46.840 --> 00:03:48.760
PROFESSOR: It is Dieter Rams.

00:03:48.760 --> 00:03:51.060
Absolutely.

00:03:51.060 --> 00:03:54.140
Dieter Rams and Johnny Ive--
two very important people.

00:03:54.140 --> 00:03:56.810
Let's show you a
little bit about them.

00:03:56.810 --> 00:04:00.450
Dieter Rams was born
in 1932 in Germany.

00:04:00.450 --> 00:04:02.480
And he's closely
associated with something

00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:06.730
called the functionalist
school of industrial design.

00:04:06.730 --> 00:04:08.900
He made these things.

00:04:08.900 --> 00:04:11.920
Johnny Ive was born
a lot later in 1967.

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:13.890
And you're all
familiar with his work

00:04:13.890 --> 00:04:16.709
from having experienced it
firsthand or seen it firsthand.

00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:23.350
These are Dieter Rams' work.

00:04:23.350 --> 00:04:26.930
These are Johnny Ive's work.

00:04:26.930 --> 00:04:27.790
Let's do that again.

00:04:27.790 --> 00:04:30.912
This is what Dieter Rams made.

00:04:30.912 --> 00:04:35.780
And, interestingly enough,
Johnny Ives made these.

00:04:35.780 --> 00:04:38.980
Do you notice any parallels?

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:41.440
Let's take a look some more.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:42.740
Johnny Ive on the right.

00:04:42.740 --> 00:04:45.850
Dieter Rams on the left.

00:04:45.850 --> 00:04:47.832
Johnny Ive on the right.

00:04:47.832 --> 00:04:50.160
Dieter Rams on the left.

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:54.120
And would you believe Johnny
on the right and Dieter Rams

00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:56.420
on the left?

00:04:56.420 --> 00:04:59.250
Again, Johnny Ive on the
right with a speaker that

00:04:59.250 --> 00:05:02.210
has an iPod on top of it
and a speaker over here

00:05:02.210 --> 00:05:05.750
that has a phonograph on it.

00:05:05.750 --> 00:05:06.750
An iMac.

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:07.790
A speaker.

00:05:07.790 --> 00:05:08.770
Johnny Ive.

00:05:08.770 --> 00:05:10.220
Dieter Rams.

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:11.410
Johnny Ive on the right.

00:05:11.410 --> 00:05:12.870
It's like a television.

00:05:12.870 --> 00:05:14.620
Doesn't it look
like a television?

00:05:14.620 --> 00:05:15.950
And here it's a television.

00:05:15.950 --> 00:05:20.110
So this interesting.

00:05:20.110 --> 00:05:23.390
That's a speaker I guess.

00:05:23.390 --> 00:05:24.944
What is this product?

00:05:24.944 --> 00:05:25.700
AUDIENCE: An iPod.

00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:26.630
PROFESSOR: It is an iPod.

00:05:26.630 --> 00:05:27.530
And what is this product?

00:05:27.530 --> 00:05:28.280
AUDIENCE: A radio.

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:29.620
PROFESSOR: It's a radio.

00:05:29.620 --> 00:05:30.800
It's a radio.

00:05:30.800 --> 00:05:33.587
So here's the question.

00:05:33.587 --> 00:05:35.670
They didn't talk about
this for a very long time--

00:05:35.670 --> 00:05:36.794
Johnny Ive and Dieter Rams.

00:05:36.794 --> 00:05:39.270
So we're going to put
ourselves back up a few months

00:05:39.270 --> 00:05:42.504
or a few years ago when no
one knew what's going on here

00:05:42.504 --> 00:05:43.920
or how they felt
about each other.

00:05:46.790 --> 00:05:49.480
What do you think about this?

00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:52.588
What do you think about
this when you see this?

00:05:52.588 --> 00:05:53.754
AUDIENCE: Legally different.

00:05:58.070 --> 00:05:59.420
PROFESSOR: Legally different?

00:05:59.420 --> 00:06:00.067
Legally.

00:06:00.067 --> 00:06:00.900
What does that mean?

00:06:04.302 --> 00:06:06.302
AUDIENCE: It wouldn't be
copyright infringement.

00:06:06.302 --> 00:06:08.093
PROFESSOR: It's not
copyright infringement.

00:06:08.093 --> 00:06:09.440
Yeah, totally different.

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:11.342
These look totally
different from each other.

00:06:11.342 --> 00:06:12.800
I know there's no
way you could see

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:17.524
any similarity in this
corpus of work at all.

00:06:17.524 --> 00:06:19.690
Don't tell the Apple lawyers
who are suing Samsung--

00:06:19.690 --> 00:06:22.840
or who sued Samsung
successfully.

00:06:22.840 --> 00:06:23.340
What else?

00:06:23.340 --> 00:06:24.890
What else do you think
of when you see this?

00:06:24.890 --> 00:06:25.230
Yes.

00:06:25.230 --> 00:06:26.690
AUDIENCE: Good
design is repeated.

00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:27.700
PROFESSOR: Good
design is repeated.

00:06:27.700 --> 00:06:29.000
What do you mean by repeated?

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:29.980
AUDIENCE: Used again.

00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:30.960
PROFESSOR: That's pretty clever.

00:06:30.960 --> 00:06:31.460
Used again.

00:06:31.460 --> 00:06:33.654
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:33.654 --> 00:06:34.570
PROFESSOR: It's very--

00:06:34.570 --> 00:06:38.057
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:06:40.327 --> 00:06:42.160
PROFESSOR: So she's
saying that good design,

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:43.785
you just use the same
thing over again.

00:06:43.785 --> 00:06:44.650
AUDIENCE: No.

00:06:44.650 --> 00:06:45.270
PROFESSOR: No.

00:06:45.270 --> 00:06:46.290
Not quite?

00:06:46.290 --> 00:06:46.970
Am I shading it?

00:06:46.970 --> 00:06:47.469
OK.

00:06:47.469 --> 00:06:50.159
Let's see what-- go ahead.

00:06:50.159 --> 00:06:51.200
AUDIENCE: No, that's all.

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:52.240
PROFESSOR: OK, fine.

00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:53.590
If you think of
something, let me know.

00:06:53.590 --> 00:06:54.879
AUDIENCE: As long
as you don't have

00:06:54.879 --> 00:06:56.404
to redesign the
wheel, [INAUDIBLE]?

00:06:59.380 --> 00:07:01.960
PROFESSOR: So adapting
designs for what you need, OK.

00:07:01.960 --> 00:07:04.700
What else?

00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:07.690
AUDIENCE: While the designs
are very similar and shared

00:07:07.690 --> 00:07:10.120
between them, the products
themselves are very different.

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:10.390
PROFESSOR: Ah.

00:07:10.390 --> 00:07:13.015
He says the designs are similar
but the products are different.

00:07:13.015 --> 00:07:14.140
Tell me.

00:07:14.140 --> 00:07:17.650
I see a music player on
the left and a music player

00:07:17.650 --> 00:07:19.320
on the right.

00:07:19.320 --> 00:07:20.990
This one fits in your pocket.

00:07:20.990 --> 00:07:23.580
This one fits in your pocket.

00:07:23.580 --> 00:07:25.554
This one has a circular
thing that spins

00:07:25.554 --> 00:07:27.220
and this is a circular
thing that spins.

00:07:27.220 --> 00:07:28.140
This allows you to select stuff.

00:07:28.140 --> 00:07:30.820
That circle and this circle
allows you to select stuff.

00:07:30.820 --> 00:07:32.237
Tell me are they different?

00:07:32.237 --> 00:07:33.112
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:37.881 --> 00:07:39.130
PROFESSOR: A little different.

00:07:39.130 --> 00:07:40.440
Sure.

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:44.390
Because it's a screen
over here on the right.

00:07:44.390 --> 00:07:46.060
And a hard drive, yes.

00:07:46.060 --> 00:07:47.700
Actually it's kind of funny.

00:07:47.700 --> 00:07:54.270
Right now, interestingly, if you
buy an iPod Touch or something,

00:07:54.270 --> 00:07:57.780
you don't have to have
music on your iPod.

00:07:57.780 --> 00:08:02.325
It streams it wirelessly over
the air much like a radio.

00:08:05.775 --> 00:08:07.580
Fascinatingly similar.

00:08:07.580 --> 00:08:08.830
Everything old is new again.

00:08:08.830 --> 00:08:12.020
So you say they're different,
but they're kind of similar.

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:12.520
What else?

00:08:16.407 --> 00:08:17.990
How do you think
they feel about this?

00:08:17.990 --> 00:08:20.570
How do you think
that Dieter Rams felt

00:08:20.570 --> 00:08:23.864
when he saw these
things coming out?

00:08:23.864 --> 00:08:24.530
AUDIENCE: Happy?

00:08:24.530 --> 00:08:25.360
PROFESSOR: Happy.

00:08:25.360 --> 00:08:26.476
Why happy?

00:08:26.476 --> 00:08:28.860
AUDIENCE: He insprired a whole
new generation of design.

00:08:28.860 --> 00:08:29.818
PROFESSOR: There we go.

00:08:29.818 --> 00:08:33.940
So he says, I'm so glad you're
copying all my hardware.

00:08:33.940 --> 00:08:36.039
I feel like I've really,
really contributed

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:37.707
a lot more to society
because of this.

00:08:37.707 --> 00:08:38.790
That's one interpretation.

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:45.910
What if someone was sitting
next to you during a test

00:08:45.910 --> 00:08:47.760
and took that philosophy?

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:51.240
Would you feel happy about the
fact that they were inspiring

00:08:51.240 --> 00:08:53.669
a whole new set of A's?

00:08:53.669 --> 00:08:54.210
I don't know.

00:08:56.810 --> 00:09:00.380
At what point have you ever
made something or thought, hey,

00:09:00.380 --> 00:09:03.060
you're copying our stuff?

00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:05.532
AUDIENCE: You want to look at
whoever wrote the textbook.

00:09:05.532 --> 00:09:07.990
You're reading the textbook
and putting down the knowledge.

00:09:07.990 --> 00:09:10.870
You're stealing from them.

00:09:10.870 --> 00:09:12.239
PROFESSOR: I don't know.

00:09:12.239 --> 00:09:12.780
I don't know.

00:09:12.780 --> 00:09:13.613
This is interesting.

00:09:13.613 --> 00:09:17.080
So we have these things that
definitely seem very similar.

00:09:19.710 --> 00:09:25.460
But what's interesting
is that they both believe

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:28.010
in the same
fundamental approaches

00:09:28.010 --> 00:09:30.140
to how to design great stuff.

00:09:30.140 --> 00:09:32.410
And they might have come
to similar conclusions

00:09:32.410 --> 00:09:37.860
either knowingly, because
of this form factor,

00:09:37.860 --> 00:09:40.770
maybe somewhat unknowingly
and they realized,

00:09:40.770 --> 00:09:43.420
boy this looks a
little bit like this,

00:09:43.420 --> 00:09:45.160
what can we learn from that.

00:09:45.160 --> 00:09:47.167
What is step number two?

00:09:47.167 --> 00:09:48.500
AUDIENCE: The information phase.

00:09:48.500 --> 00:09:49.410
PROFESSOR: The
information phase, yes.

00:09:49.410 --> 00:09:50.480
The information phase.

00:09:50.480 --> 00:09:52.396
So how can we leverage
what's out in the world

00:09:52.396 --> 00:09:53.910
already to inform our design?

00:09:53.910 --> 00:09:57.330
And they might have looked at--
I don't know-- 50 or 100 or 200

00:09:57.330 --> 00:09:59.830
different ideas and came on
this one or a group of them

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:00.390
that looked like this.

00:10:00.390 --> 00:10:02.306
And he said, it reminds
me of this other thing

00:10:02.306 --> 00:10:04.380
that I saw a long time
ago, when I was a kid.

00:10:04.380 --> 00:10:07.100
And I loved the way it worked.

00:10:07.100 --> 00:10:07.805
So yes.

00:10:07.805 --> 00:10:09.180
I think you're
right about this--

00:10:09.180 --> 00:10:13.220
that great design has
a lot of similarities.

00:10:13.220 --> 00:10:15.650
And you'll see this
happening throughout history.

00:10:15.650 --> 00:10:18.490
Things change very
little in history.

00:10:18.490 --> 00:10:21.280
There are few changes that
occur-- fundamental changes.

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:24.180
Take a look at kitchens.

00:10:24.180 --> 00:10:27.230
Kitchens in the past-- I
don't know, let's say 60,

00:10:27.230 --> 00:10:30.460
70 years-- have only
had really two changes

00:10:30.460 --> 00:10:32.160
that are substantive.

00:10:32.160 --> 00:10:34.480
One of them is that there
are now-- almost always when

00:10:34.480 --> 00:10:36.885
the new kitchens are
designed-- open to another room

00:10:36.885 --> 00:10:38.640
or to an area where
people can entertain.

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:41.130
People use the kitchen
differently now

00:10:41.130 --> 00:10:43.010
as a way of connecting
with people.

00:10:43.010 --> 00:10:44.500
Before, you'd shut
off the kitchen.

00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:45.420
You close the door.

00:10:45.420 --> 00:10:46.650
And you bring out the food.

00:10:46.650 --> 00:10:49.025
And you say, look at this
beautiful food and not the mess

00:10:49.025 --> 00:10:50.280
in the kitchen.

00:10:50.280 --> 00:10:51.020
That changed.

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:53.710
And microwave ovens changed.

00:10:53.710 --> 00:10:55.630
Who here has a microwave oven?

00:10:55.630 --> 00:10:56.710
Wow.

00:10:56.710 --> 00:10:58.900
And who here has
a microwave oven

00:10:58.900 --> 00:11:00.544
and doesn't have
their own kitchen?

00:11:00.544 --> 00:11:02.210
So some of you don't
even have a kitchen

00:11:02.210 --> 00:11:03.040
and you've got a microwave oven.

00:11:03.040 --> 00:11:03.747
Pretty amazing.

00:11:03.747 --> 00:11:04.580
That's a big change.

00:11:04.580 --> 00:11:07.490
Otherwise, we've
got refrigeration.

00:11:07.490 --> 00:11:08.777
We've got a stove.

00:11:08.777 --> 00:11:10.860
About the same height as
all the stoves before it.

00:11:10.860 --> 00:11:13.530
We've got ovens.

00:11:13.530 --> 00:11:16.557
If you're rich, you
might have two ovens.

00:11:16.557 --> 00:11:18.140
Maybe you have a
garbage disposal now,

00:11:18.140 --> 00:11:19.848
but there's not a
whole bunch of changes.

00:11:19.848 --> 00:11:21.290
Things change very slowly.

00:11:21.290 --> 00:11:23.050
So we'll see this in design.

00:11:23.050 --> 00:11:25.276
And what's interesting is
that Dieter Rams came up

00:11:25.276 --> 00:11:28.310
with these 10 principles
of good design.

00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:30.090
So let's discuss them.

00:11:30.090 --> 00:11:34.030
I want you to tell me, for
each of these principles,

00:11:34.030 --> 00:11:40.455
what you think they mean and
if you think they're any good.

00:11:40.455 --> 00:11:44.550
Good design is innovative.

00:11:44.550 --> 00:11:46.675
What does that mean that
good design is innovative?

00:11:49.625 --> 00:11:50.250
How about this.

00:11:50.250 --> 00:11:52.430
Who thinks good design is
not innovative-- does not

00:11:52.430 --> 00:11:53.346
have to be innovative?

00:11:56.460 --> 00:11:58.292
Give me some example.

00:11:58.292 --> 00:11:59.284
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:11:59.284 --> 00:12:00.276
PROFESSOR: Sure.

00:12:00.276 --> 00:12:02.650
To prove that good design does
not have to be innovative.

00:12:02.650 --> 00:12:06.100
AUDIENCE: The one
you just showed us?

00:12:06.100 --> 00:12:08.780
PROFESSOR: So you're
saying that this was not

00:12:08.780 --> 00:12:10.754
an innovation over this?

00:12:10.754 --> 00:12:11.920
AUDIENCE: Well, parts of it.

00:12:11.920 --> 00:12:13.120
PROFESSOR: Part of it.

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:15.150
What part?

00:12:15.150 --> 00:12:16.290
AUDIENCE: The way it looks.

00:12:16.290 --> 00:12:17.520
PROFESSOR: Is innovative?

00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:18.213
Or not innovate?

00:12:21.310 --> 00:12:24.220
AUDIENCE: Not if you're
comparing it to the other one.

00:12:24.220 --> 00:12:25.400
PROFESSOR: How come?

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:27.000
This is made of plastic.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:28.650
This has different
kinds of plastic.

00:12:28.650 --> 00:12:30.340
It's got a screen on it.

00:12:30.340 --> 00:12:32.405
It's got four buttons
on the outside.

00:12:32.405 --> 00:12:34.530
It's got headphones that
are attached to it instead

00:12:34.530 --> 00:12:37.560
of using a speaker.

00:12:37.560 --> 00:12:39.624
You think it's too similar?

00:12:39.624 --> 00:12:41.665
AUDIENCE: No, I'm saying
that it's as innovative.

00:12:41.665 --> 00:12:43.748
I think it doesn't have
to be extremely innovative

00:12:43.748 --> 00:12:45.570
because I'm saying
they look very similar.

00:12:45.570 --> 00:12:48.695
There are innovations
but they're not drastic.

00:12:48.695 --> 00:12:50.320
PROFESSOR: Would you
say an iPod is not

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:52.340
a drastic innovation
over a radio?

00:12:52.340 --> 00:12:54.580
AUDIENCE: Yes, I'm
saying it is, but I'm

00:12:54.580 --> 00:12:56.400
saying the physical
appearance of it.

00:12:56.400 --> 00:12:57.816
PROFESSOR: The
physical appearance

00:12:57.816 --> 00:12:59.480
may not be innovative.

00:12:59.480 --> 00:13:00.230
Other examples?

00:13:00.230 --> 00:13:03.890
I'm going to bring this
other slide back up.

00:13:03.890 --> 00:13:04.882
Yes.

00:13:04.882 --> 00:13:06.507
AUDIENCE: Some of
the things that we've

00:13:06.507 --> 00:13:10.338
been using since forever,
like a bowl or something--

00:13:10.338 --> 00:13:12.830
it's really basic but I
think it's good design.

00:13:12.830 --> 00:13:14.702
PROFESSOR: A bowl
is a good design.

00:13:14.702 --> 00:13:16.655
But if someone made a new bowl--

00:13:18.912 --> 00:13:20.370
AUDIENCE: It could
be a good design

00:13:20.370 --> 00:13:23.800
and innovate but I don't
think it's required.

00:13:23.800 --> 00:13:25.540
PROFESSOR: You
don't it's required?

00:13:25.540 --> 00:13:29.420
So a new bowl doesn't have to be
innovative to be well designed

00:13:29.420 --> 00:13:30.650
or to be a good design.

00:13:30.650 --> 00:13:31.613
That's interesting.

00:13:31.613 --> 00:13:33.585
AUDIENCE: To go back
to the last example,

00:13:33.585 --> 00:13:35.557
innovation also
depends on the context

00:13:35.557 --> 00:13:37.040
when you're looking
at the design.

00:13:37.040 --> 00:13:38.190
PROFESSOR: What do
you mean the context

00:13:38.190 --> 00:13:39.250
in looking at the design?

00:13:39.250 --> 00:13:40.490
What do you mean it
depends on the context?

00:13:40.490 --> 00:13:42.531
AUDIENCE: So right now,
before I saw Dieter Rams,

00:13:42.531 --> 00:13:44.837
I was of the opposite
position of Johnny Ives.

00:13:44.837 --> 00:13:47.252
But now I that I see a
different context, maybe I see

00:13:47.252 --> 00:13:49.312
[INAUDIBLE]

00:13:49.312 --> 00:13:50.270
PROFESSOR: Interesting.

00:13:50.270 --> 00:13:51.061
That's interesting.

00:13:51.061 --> 00:13:52.280
Context.

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:53.620
What do you mean context, now?

00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:55.817
What's your context?

00:13:55.817 --> 00:13:58.150
AUDIENCE: It's what I know
about those kinds of designs.

00:13:58.150 --> 00:13:59.620
PROFESSOR: It's what you know.

00:13:59.620 --> 00:14:01.262
Context about what you know.

00:14:01.262 --> 00:14:04.015
Could it be something
else as well?

00:14:04.015 --> 00:14:05.665
AUDIENCE: Context
of similar designs

00:14:05.665 --> 00:14:07.480
and their past designs
related to that.

00:14:07.480 --> 00:14:09.680
PROFESSOR: A broader context.

00:14:09.680 --> 00:14:11.065
What else?

00:14:11.065 --> 00:14:11.565
Yes.

00:14:11.565 --> 00:14:14.065
AUDIENCE: I would have to argue
that this design is innovate

00:14:14.065 --> 00:14:17.052
because if a design is very
good, then there is no reason

00:14:17.052 --> 00:14:18.480
you want to improve it.

00:14:18.480 --> 00:14:20.700
PROFESSOR: If a design is
very good if there's no?

00:14:20.700 --> 00:14:21.670
AUDIENCE: There's no
reason to improve it.

00:14:21.670 --> 00:14:23.010
PROFESSOR: No reason
to improve it.

00:14:23.010 --> 00:14:24.390
AUDIENCE: If you come
up with something that's

00:14:24.390 --> 00:14:26.290
good than from
what is was before

00:14:26.290 --> 00:14:29.479
and it's selling
well then there's

00:14:29.479 --> 00:14:30.520
clearly some improvement.

00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:33.460
PROFESSOR: She said if
you have a new product

00:14:33.460 --> 00:14:35.620
and it's selling
well then there's

00:14:35.620 --> 00:14:36.920
clearly some improvement.

00:14:36.920 --> 00:14:38.950
What if it's not
selling so well?

00:14:38.950 --> 00:14:40.162
Could it be innovative?

00:14:40.162 --> 00:14:41.703
AUDIENCE: It could
also be innovative

00:14:41.703 --> 00:14:45.464
because I think the innovation
is defined-- well, not defined,

00:14:45.464 --> 00:14:50.007
but it about when you decide
that needs to be redesigned.

00:14:50.007 --> 00:14:51.590
PROFESSOR: Innovation
comes about when

00:14:51.590 --> 00:14:53.040
you decide it needs
to be redesigned.

00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:53.540
Interesting.

00:14:57.250 --> 00:14:59.800
Other ideas?

00:14:59.800 --> 00:15:01.850
I think context is
very interesting here

00:15:01.850 --> 00:15:04.490
and a little unusual.

00:15:04.490 --> 00:15:08.570
Context-- we look at the
world in a certain way.

00:15:08.570 --> 00:15:12.460
By a show of hands
here, who thinks

00:15:12.460 --> 00:15:16.300
that their hairstyle
looks ridiculous?

00:15:16.300 --> 00:15:20.230
There are no hands that went up.

00:15:20.230 --> 00:15:23.090
Who here thinks that people
whose-- they see pictures

00:15:23.090 --> 00:15:26.860
of people from the '80s
have ridiculous hairstyles?

00:15:26.860 --> 00:15:28.270
Yeah, a lot more
hands go up now.

00:15:28.270 --> 00:15:30.450
How about the '70s?

00:15:30.450 --> 00:15:33.166
So you don't think that in 20
years you're going to look back

00:15:33.166 --> 00:15:35.790
at pictures of yourself and go,
I cannot believe my hair looked

00:15:35.790 --> 00:15:38.140
like that?

00:15:38.140 --> 00:15:39.580
Context, right?

00:15:39.580 --> 00:15:41.950
Context of our society.

00:15:41.950 --> 00:15:45.025
Angel goes, no way,
his hair looks great.

00:15:45.025 --> 00:15:45.650
That's awesome.

00:15:45.650 --> 00:15:46.899
I'm always keeping this thing.

00:15:46.899 --> 00:15:48.010
And he may.

00:15:48.010 --> 00:15:49.706
He may keep that.

00:15:49.706 --> 00:15:51.830
Some things are a little
more timeless than others.

00:15:51.830 --> 00:15:55.660
Do you know something
interesting about art forgery?

00:15:55.660 --> 00:15:57.410
Anyone know a lot
about art forgery?

00:15:57.410 --> 00:16:01.010
So if there's a piece of
art from the-- let's say,

00:16:01.010 --> 00:16:05.860
early 1800s-- and let's
suppose it's now 1920.

00:16:05.860 --> 00:16:11.070
And I have hired Jacob
to forge a piece of art--

00:16:11.070 --> 00:16:12.920
he's a great art forger.

00:16:12.920 --> 00:16:16.570
Well, if he's great, at the time
when they had these forgeries,

00:16:16.570 --> 00:16:19.990
you wouldn't be able to
tell that it was a forgery.

00:16:22.710 --> 00:16:27.290
But 30, 40, 50 years later, you
say, oh, that's the forgery.

00:16:27.290 --> 00:16:28.540
I can tell.

00:16:28.540 --> 00:16:32.410
Because unconsciously, Jacob
sees the world around him

00:16:32.410 --> 00:16:37.040
and he begins to put in
elements of contemporary design

00:16:37.040 --> 00:16:38.500
into that piece.

00:16:38.500 --> 00:16:41.720
And 50 years later, the
context has changed,

00:16:41.720 --> 00:16:42.670
and you can see it.

00:16:42.670 --> 00:16:45.330
You can see the stuff in there.

00:16:45.330 --> 00:16:47.380
You can see those
differences and everything

00:16:47.380 --> 00:16:49.750
he's done to balance out
all the small differences.

00:16:49.750 --> 00:16:52.070
And it looks like a forgery.

00:16:52.070 --> 00:16:53.780
It's pretty amazing.

00:16:53.780 --> 00:16:55.037
So maybe this is true.

00:16:55.037 --> 00:16:55.870
Maybe it's not true.

00:16:55.870 --> 00:16:56.390
How about this one?

00:16:56.390 --> 00:16:57.848
Good design makes
a product useful.

00:16:57.848 --> 00:17:00.330
Is that true?

00:17:00.330 --> 00:17:02.950
Who thinks it's not true?

00:17:02.950 --> 00:17:04.970
Who thinks it is true?

00:17:04.970 --> 00:17:06.020
What does it mean?

00:17:06.020 --> 00:17:08.506
What does it mean to be useful?

00:17:08.506 --> 00:17:10.256
I want to know what
it means to be useful.

00:17:10.256 --> 00:17:11.484
AUDIENCE: Satifies a need.

00:17:11.484 --> 00:17:12.650
PROFESSOR: Satisfies a need.

00:17:16.530 --> 00:17:19.286
Tell me more about that.

00:17:19.286 --> 00:17:19.869
What's a need?

00:17:23.140 --> 00:17:30.030
Do I need to listen to all
my music wherever I am?

00:17:30.030 --> 00:17:32.270
I kind of need to.

00:17:32.270 --> 00:17:34.820
I get bored easily.

00:17:34.820 --> 00:17:37.050
Satisfies a need
or maybe something

00:17:37.050 --> 00:17:39.420
less serious than a need.

00:17:39.420 --> 00:17:41.570
AUDIENCE: If it adds value.

00:17:41.570 --> 00:17:43.139
PROFESSOR: Adds value.

00:17:43.139 --> 00:17:44.430
What does it mean to add value?

00:17:44.430 --> 00:17:45.275
What is value?

00:17:49.860 --> 00:17:50.400
Any ideas?

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:52.368
Anyone?

00:17:52.368 --> 00:17:54.340
AUDIENCE: Performs an
action efficiently.

00:17:54.340 --> 00:17:57.016
PROFESSOR: Performs
an action efficiently.

00:17:57.016 --> 00:17:59.040
Does art perform an
action efficiently?

00:18:02.330 --> 00:18:04.516
AUDIENCE: It depends on
how if art is useful.

00:18:04.516 --> 00:18:05.390
PROFESSOR: Well, yes.

00:18:05.390 --> 00:18:06.020
Is art useful?

00:18:06.020 --> 00:18:06.780
I don't know.

00:18:06.780 --> 00:18:07.630
Is art design?

00:18:07.630 --> 00:18:09.380
Oh, different topic.

00:18:09.380 --> 00:18:12.370
Reserved for a different day.

00:18:12.370 --> 00:18:13.095
What else?

00:18:13.095 --> 00:18:14.970
AUDIENCE: It does what
it was designed to do.

00:18:14.970 --> 00:18:16.053
PROFESSOR: Designed to do.

00:18:16.053 --> 00:18:17.559
It does what it
was designed to do.

00:18:17.559 --> 00:18:19.100
So good design makes
a product useful

00:18:19.100 --> 00:18:22.800
because it's doing what
it's supposed to do.

00:18:22.800 --> 00:18:25.129
It has fulfilled its
intended purpose.

00:18:25.129 --> 00:18:28.552
AUDIENCE: I think I'd like
to argue that because I think

00:18:28.552 --> 00:18:32.464
that you could have a useful
product that has a purpose that

00:18:32.464 --> 00:18:34.460
wasn't intended by
the manufacturer.

00:18:34.460 --> 00:18:36.350
PROFESSOR: A useful
product whose purpose

00:18:36.350 --> 00:18:38.750
was not intended by
the manufacturer.

00:18:38.750 --> 00:18:39.738
Let's consider this.

00:18:42.880 --> 00:18:44.940
This is risky.

00:18:44.940 --> 00:18:49.850
This is a brand new Apple
Macintosh Retina Display

00:18:49.850 --> 00:18:54.940
MacBook Pro which I'm going
to use as a door stop.

00:18:57.560 --> 00:18:58.200
Oh, yeah.

00:19:03.410 --> 00:19:03.940
Not int--

00:19:03.940 --> 00:19:09.140
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:09.140 --> 00:19:11.527
Can we get a close
up on that one?

00:19:11.527 --> 00:19:12.610
Can we see this over here?

00:19:12.610 --> 00:19:14.318
I don't know if you
can see it down here.

00:19:14.318 --> 00:19:16.900
This is my pride and joy here
being used as a door stop.

00:19:16.900 --> 00:19:19.760
Not intended by
the manufacturer.

00:19:19.760 --> 00:19:21.850
Pretty useful if we need
to prop open the door

00:19:21.850 --> 00:19:25.190
I suppose I could prop it open.

00:19:25.190 --> 00:19:27.360
Oh god, that scraping
sound sounds terrible.

00:19:30.590 --> 00:19:31.920
Anything for you guys.

00:19:31.920 --> 00:19:32.550
Anything.

00:19:32.550 --> 00:19:35.200
So look how nice it
props the door open

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:36.700
if we didn't have
something else.

00:19:36.700 --> 00:19:38.850
Again, not intended
by the manufacturer

00:19:38.850 --> 00:19:41.583
who had to work on the
tolerances of this device.

00:19:48.950 --> 00:19:50.700
So that's interesting.

00:19:53.320 --> 00:19:56.730
What if it didn't performance
its intended action

00:19:56.730 --> 00:19:58.539
and I found a new use for it?

00:19:58.539 --> 00:19:59.330
Is it still useful?

00:20:02.546 --> 00:20:05.680
I could have an Acer or
something that I would think--

00:20:05.680 --> 00:20:08.127
or maybe a five-year-old
Acer that's very, very slow

00:20:08.127 --> 00:20:10.710
and doesn't work very well and
I need to get rid of it anyway.

00:20:10.710 --> 00:20:11.200
And it's broke.

00:20:11.200 --> 00:20:11.910
It's falling apart.

00:20:11.910 --> 00:20:14.368
And the screen-- every time I
move it the screen falls off.

00:20:14.368 --> 00:20:17.000
And I can take it and make
it a very useful doorstep.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.622
Not its intended purpose at all.

00:20:19.622 --> 00:20:22.110
AUDIENCE: I still don't think
that it's a good design just

00:20:22.110 --> 00:20:25.577
because it has a use, though,
because you used it as a door

00:20:25.577 --> 00:20:29.074
stop but I still don't think
that is one of the best

00:20:29.074 --> 00:20:30.120
choices for a door stop.

00:20:30.120 --> 00:20:31.170
PROFESSOR: You don't think
it's the best choice for a door

00:20:31.170 --> 00:20:31.670
stop?

00:20:31.670 --> 00:20:34.230
I think it's a
beautiful door stop.

00:20:34.230 --> 00:20:35.626
Maybe the MacBook Air is better.

00:20:35.626 --> 00:20:36.375
It's wedge shaped.

00:20:38.843 --> 00:20:40.676
AUDIENCE: I think the
connotations of design

00:20:40.676 --> 00:20:41.770
is purposeful.

00:20:41.770 --> 00:20:45.005
So if you use it for
an unintended use,

00:20:45.005 --> 00:20:47.460
I don't think it's
considered a good thing.

00:20:47.460 --> 00:20:48.330
PROFESSOR: If I use it
for an unintended use,

00:20:48.330 --> 00:20:49.340
it's not good design.

00:20:49.340 --> 00:20:50.576
Why not?

00:20:50.576 --> 00:20:52.492
AUDIENCE: Because when
a designer is designing

00:20:52.492 --> 00:20:54.325
a product, they have a
specific use in mind.

00:20:54.325 --> 00:20:56.000
And they're trying
to achieve that goal.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:00.517
If they don't achieve that goal
and then achieve another goal--

00:21:00.517 --> 00:21:03.100
PROFESSOR: What if they achieve
something far better, far more

00:21:03.100 --> 00:21:04.540
noble, far more incredible?

00:21:04.540 --> 00:21:05.980
AUDIENCE: That's not what
they were trying to do.

00:21:05.980 --> 00:21:07.730
PROFESSOR: I know but
is it good anyway?

00:21:07.730 --> 00:21:09.620
Does it matter what the
intent is is the question.

00:21:09.620 --> 00:21:11.411
AUDIENCE: I think it
does matter what the--

00:21:11.411 --> 00:21:13.210
PROFESSOR: You think
intent matters.

00:21:13.210 --> 00:21:16.160
Who thinks intent matters?

00:21:16.160 --> 00:21:18.250
Who thinks intent
does not matter?

00:21:18.250 --> 00:21:19.900
Who's unsure about this?

00:21:19.900 --> 00:21:20.467
Oh, yes.

00:21:20.467 --> 00:21:22.300
This would be good for
a later conversation.

00:21:22.300 --> 00:21:23.180
Let's consider this.

00:21:23.180 --> 00:21:23.990
Good design-- now
know we're getting

00:21:23.990 --> 00:21:25.156
really crazy-- is aesthetic.

00:21:25.156 --> 00:21:27.446
What does it mean
to be aesthetic?

00:21:27.446 --> 00:21:29.320
[AUDIENCE MEMBERS RESPONDING
 SIMULTANEOUSLY]

00:21:29.320 --> 00:21:30.890
PROFESSOR: Pleasing.

00:21:30.890 --> 00:21:33.870
Pleasing in what way?

00:21:33.870 --> 00:21:34.760
AUDIENCE: Visually.

