PROFESSOR: Visually pleasing.

00:21:37.099 --> 00:21:38.580
AUDIENCE: All ways.

00:21:38.580 --> 00:21:41.110
PROFESSOR: What?

00:21:41.110 --> 00:21:42.467
AUDIENCE: All ways,

00:21:42.467 --> 00:21:44.050
PROFESSOR: Pleasing
in other ways too.

00:21:44.050 --> 00:21:46.850
Not just visually but
auditorily pleasing.

00:21:46.850 --> 00:21:51.076
Maybe the smell of a new car.

00:21:51.076 --> 00:21:52.520
You don't think
they work on that?

00:21:52.520 --> 00:21:54.000
Oh, they work on that.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:55.892
In fact, Mercedes
once was having

00:21:55.892 --> 00:21:57.850
an issue with some cars
because it didn't quite

00:21:57.850 --> 00:21:59.900
have that Mercedes smell.

00:21:59.900 --> 00:22:01.250
So they hired a nose.

00:22:01.250 --> 00:22:02.910
Anyone knows what a nose is?

00:22:02.910 --> 00:22:05.003
It's a person who
smells really well.

00:22:05.003 --> 00:22:06.586
And it's about one
in-- I don't know--

00:22:06.586 --> 00:22:08.919
100,000 people or 500,000
people or a million people who

00:22:08.919 --> 00:22:10.910
have this great ability
to smell things well.

00:22:10.910 --> 00:22:12.119
And the nose went to the car.

00:22:12.119 --> 00:22:13.076
And they took this car.

00:22:13.076 --> 00:22:15.590
They shipped it from wherever
the car person, owner was.

00:22:15.590 --> 00:22:16.580
They gave her a different car.

00:22:16.580 --> 00:22:17.455
They shipped it down.

00:22:17.455 --> 00:22:20.870
And she [SNIFFING] smelled
all around the car.

00:22:20.870 --> 00:22:22.560
Then she went, door,
take the door off.

00:22:22.560 --> 00:22:23.268
And the went, OK.

00:22:23.268 --> 00:22:24.429
They stripped the door off.

00:22:24.429 --> 00:22:25.720
She's smelling around the door.

00:22:25.720 --> 00:22:27.080
She said take this
panel off the door.

00:22:27.080 --> 00:22:28.240
They took the
panel off the door.

00:22:28.240 --> 00:22:29.739
She's smelling and
goes, this is it.

00:22:29.739 --> 00:22:32.540
This is the problem
right here, in the door.

00:22:32.540 --> 00:22:34.300
It was the insulation.

00:22:34.300 --> 00:22:35.980
And they went to the
insulation people.

00:22:35.980 --> 00:22:37.580
They said, what did you
do to our insulation.

00:22:37.580 --> 00:22:38.960
They said, we didn't do
anything to the insulation.

00:22:38.960 --> 00:22:39.950
Show us what happened.

00:22:39.950 --> 00:22:40.750
And they found out.

00:22:40.750 --> 00:22:43.920
In one part of this process,
really early on, the insulation

00:22:43.920 --> 00:22:49.170
had been stored in sacks
that had once stored tea.

00:22:49.170 --> 00:22:51.180
Oh, yeah.

00:22:51.180 --> 00:22:54.710
That new car smell,
very important.

00:22:54.710 --> 00:22:56.380
So good design is aesthetic.

00:22:56.380 --> 00:22:59.180
Who thinks this is true that
good design must be aesthetic?

00:23:01.609 --> 00:23:03.650
AUDIENCE: It's something
that you're going to use

00:23:03.650 --> 00:23:07.130
and you want it to be pleasing
in every sense of the word.

00:23:07.130 --> 00:23:07.430
PROFESSOR: You want
it to be pleasing

00:23:07.430 --> 00:23:08.555
in every sense of the word?

00:23:08.555 --> 00:23:10.520
Who thinks it's not true?

00:23:10.520 --> 00:23:11.417
Tell us why.

00:23:11.417 --> 00:23:13.875
AUDIENCE: If you look at the
inside of a motor or something

00:23:13.875 --> 00:23:16.041
that people aren't going
to look at I feel like what

00:23:16.041 --> 00:23:18.240
it physically appears
like does not matter.

00:23:18.240 --> 00:23:18.420
PROFESSOR: Great.

00:23:18.420 --> 00:23:20.450
So you're saying if you look
at the inside of a motor people

00:23:20.450 --> 00:23:21.090
where people aren't
going to look,

00:23:21.090 --> 00:23:22.970
you think it doesn't matter?

00:23:22.970 --> 00:23:25.940
There's a company that
disagrees with this philosophy.

00:23:25.940 --> 00:23:28.894
And this company
is called Apple.

00:23:28.894 --> 00:23:30.310
I bring up a lot
of Apple examples

00:23:30.310 --> 00:23:31.120
because I happen to know them.

00:23:31.120 --> 00:23:32.494
And I think it's
very interesting

00:23:32.494 --> 00:23:34.695
because we are all
familiar with them.

00:23:34.695 --> 00:23:36.070
Apple does something
interesting.

00:23:36.070 --> 00:23:39.910
With the inside of an iPhone, if
you-- I'm not going to take it

00:23:39.910 --> 00:23:42.480
apart-- I'll do a lot.

00:23:42.480 --> 00:23:44.790
But if you take
the iPhone apart,

00:23:44.790 --> 00:23:47.200
everything there matches
a certain color chart

00:23:47.200 --> 00:23:48.120
that they have.

00:23:48.120 --> 00:23:49.225
They have a color chart.

00:23:49.225 --> 00:23:50.850
And if it doesn't
match the color chart

00:23:50.850 --> 00:23:55.470
it doesn't go inside
there because they believe

00:23:55.470 --> 00:23:58.040
if you start cheating
on the inside,

00:23:58.040 --> 00:24:00.000
it'll begin to leak out.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:01.890
And that cheating
will become revealed

00:24:01.890 --> 00:24:04.290
on the outside of the design.

00:24:04.290 --> 00:24:07.240
They think the parts that you
never see are still important.

00:24:07.240 --> 00:24:09.540
When the Macintosh
first came out--

00:24:09.540 --> 00:24:11.340
it was a big object like this.

00:24:11.340 --> 00:24:13.350
A little small display.

00:24:13.350 --> 00:24:15.784
And if you were
able to open it--

00:24:15.784 --> 00:24:17.200
and it was only
meant to be opened

00:24:17.200 --> 00:24:19.782
by professionals
who are in the shop.

00:24:19.782 --> 00:24:21.740
You weren't meant to open
it because of the CRT

00:24:21.740 --> 00:24:24.186
and it can be a very
high voltage there.

00:24:24.186 --> 00:24:25.685
You open it and
take it off the back

00:24:25.685 --> 00:24:28.310
and inside is a relief
of everyone's signature

00:24:28.310 --> 00:24:31.555
who worked on that
product, inside that,

00:24:31.555 --> 00:24:33.170
that no consumer
was meant to see.

00:24:35.730 --> 00:24:38.810
Do you still think
it's unimportant?

00:24:38.810 --> 00:24:41.745
AUDIENCE: I feel like what
makes a good design would

00:24:41.745 --> 00:24:42.460
be other factors.

00:24:42.460 --> 00:24:43.950
PROFESSOR: Other factors.

00:24:43.950 --> 00:24:45.192
OK.

00:24:45.192 --> 00:24:47.192
AUDIENCE: If you're talking
about like an engine

00:24:47.192 --> 00:24:50.380
or something would you count
the sound of it as aesthetic?

00:24:50.380 --> 00:24:53.580
PROFESSOR: I would count
the sound of an engine

00:24:53.580 --> 00:24:54.200
as aesthetic.

00:24:54.200 --> 00:24:55.650
Absolutely.

00:24:55.650 --> 00:24:58.338
AUDIENCE: So I want a car that
sounds like an angry weasel.

00:24:58.338 --> 00:24:59.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:59.240 --> 00:25:01.420
PROFESSOR: You want your
car to sound a certain way.

00:25:01.420 --> 00:25:04.120
People say, oh, the
roar of the car.

00:25:04.120 --> 00:25:06.535
The roar of that V8
engine, they say.

00:25:06.535 --> 00:25:09.910
Or that distinctive Porsche
sound they talk about.

00:25:09.910 --> 00:25:10.460
Absolutely.

00:25:10.460 --> 00:25:11.709
Think of the sound of the car.

00:25:15.020 --> 00:25:16.985
Good design helps us to
understand a product.

00:25:16.985 --> 00:25:19.370
Who thinks this is true?

00:25:19.370 --> 00:25:21.560
Who thinks it's a lie?

00:25:21.560 --> 00:25:24.284
Who thinks it's not necessary?

00:25:24.284 --> 00:25:26.665
Good design helps to
understand a product, no?

00:25:26.665 --> 00:25:27.540
We all agree on this.

00:25:27.540 --> 00:25:29.340
What does it mean to
understand a product?

00:25:29.340 --> 00:25:34.346
How do I understand a
paper cup or a bowl?

00:25:34.346 --> 00:25:36.564
AUDIENCE: Well, there's
some cases in which you'll

00:25:36.564 --> 00:25:38.290
have something and
people don't usually

00:25:38.290 --> 00:25:40.460
read manuals or
anything like that.

00:25:40.460 --> 00:25:43.980
So the more intuitive
you can make the design--

00:25:43.980 --> 00:25:45.687
like make some
spot for, no, this

00:25:45.687 --> 00:25:47.020
is clearly where your hand goes.

00:25:47.020 --> 00:25:47.940
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:25:47.940 --> 00:25:48.618
Intuitive.

00:25:48.618 --> 00:25:49.993
Something where
it's clear, where

00:25:49.993 --> 00:25:52.034
you know how to interact
with it, engage with it.

00:25:54.570 --> 00:25:55.990
Good design is unobtrusive.

00:25:55.990 --> 00:25:58.610
What does it mean
to be unobtrusive?

00:25:58.610 --> 00:26:00.818
What do you mean about good
design being unobtrusive?

00:26:02.305 --> 00:26:03.680
AUDIENCE: Doesn't
get in the way?

00:26:03.680 --> 00:26:05.096
PROFESSOR: Doesn't
get in the way.

00:26:05.096 --> 00:26:06.700
Who thinks this is true?

00:26:06.700 --> 00:26:08.630
Who thinks this is not true?

00:26:08.630 --> 00:26:10.803
Can you give me an example?

00:26:10.803 --> 00:26:12.344
AUDIENCE: I think
there are buildings

00:26:12.344 --> 00:26:14.657
that are very well designed
and they're very obtrusive.

00:26:14.657 --> 00:26:16.115
PROFESSOR: Obtrusive
buildings that

00:26:16.115 --> 00:26:18.160
are well designed but obtrusive.

00:26:18.160 --> 00:26:22.160
What does it mean in that
context to be obtrusive?

00:26:22.160 --> 00:26:27.815
AUDIENCE: They can obstruct
traffic, other buildings,

00:26:27.815 --> 00:26:28.810
other--

00:26:28.810 --> 00:26:30.740
PROFESSOR: They could
be obtrusive in terms

00:26:30.740 --> 00:26:32.404
of the visual line.

00:26:32.404 --> 00:26:33.820
Well some designs
are interesting.

00:26:37.250 --> 00:26:41.740
This design is somewhat
obtrusive, particularly

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:44.314
when it's being used.

00:26:44.314 --> 00:26:46.230
If anyone here has ever
been in an environment

00:26:46.230 --> 00:26:48.100
where someone pulled
the fire alarm,

00:26:48.100 --> 00:26:52.020
you'll know how obtrusive
a fire alarm can be.

00:26:52.020 --> 00:26:53.730
But it's pretty good
because it needs

00:26:53.730 --> 00:26:55.660
to be at that time
and not now, which

00:26:55.660 --> 00:26:59.368
is why it's trying to be
a little bit more quiet.

00:26:59.368 --> 00:27:01.742
It could be even better maybe
if we didn't see it at all.

00:27:01.742 --> 00:27:02.242
Maybe.

00:27:02.242 --> 00:27:02.960
I'm not sure.

00:27:02.960 --> 00:27:05.540
There must be a reason why
they all have to be red.

00:27:05.540 --> 00:27:06.934
I don't know what
that reason is.

00:27:06.934 --> 00:27:08.767
AUDIENCE: I don't think
that premise applies

00:27:08.767 --> 00:27:11.177
when part of your design is
to make something obtrusive.

00:27:11.177 --> 00:27:13.510
PROFESSOR: When do you want
to make something obtrusive?

00:27:13.510 --> 00:27:14.220
Give me an example.

00:27:14.220 --> 00:27:15.320
AUDIENCE: When you
have a fire alarm.

00:27:15.320 --> 00:27:16.820
PROFESSOR: Well
we're trying to make

00:27:16.820 --> 00:27:18.320
it minimally obtrusive, right?

00:27:18.320 --> 00:27:19.611
They could've made it this big.

00:27:23.090 --> 00:27:25.607
It could be coming
out of the wall.

00:27:25.607 --> 00:27:27.190
It could go off every
hour just to let

00:27:27.190 --> 00:27:28.810
you know everything's cool.

00:27:32.620 --> 00:27:34.750
What if they made
it half the size?

00:27:34.750 --> 00:27:36.600
Or they could make
it even smaller.

00:27:36.600 --> 00:27:39.501
Wouldn't that be better?

00:27:39.501 --> 00:27:40.000
Maybe.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:41.294
OK.

00:27:41.294 --> 00:27:43.825
AUDIENCE: If you're Apple, yeah.

00:27:43.825 --> 00:27:45.200
PROFESSOR: Good
design is honest.

00:27:45.200 --> 00:27:45.700
Whoa.

00:27:45.700 --> 00:27:48.349
What does it mean to be
honest in your design?

00:27:48.349 --> 00:27:49.640
What does it mean to be honest?

00:27:49.640 --> 00:27:50.556
Good design is honest.

00:27:54.312 --> 00:27:55.975
AUDIENCE: If something
looks like it's

00:27:55.975 --> 00:27:58.350
supposed to be doing a specific
thing it shouldn't do something

00:27:58.350 --> 00:27:58.830
else.

00:27:58.830 --> 00:28:00.760
PROFESSOR: So something looks
like it should do something,

00:28:00.760 --> 00:28:02.301
it shouldn't be
doing something else.

00:28:02.301 --> 00:28:05.560
So I shouldn't walk up
to this and say, oh, you

00:28:05.560 --> 00:28:07.570
got a beautiful door stop.

00:28:07.570 --> 00:28:11.340
I've been looking for
a door stop all day.

00:28:11.340 --> 00:28:13.812
What else?

00:28:13.812 --> 00:28:15.520
AUDIENCE: If it promises
to do something,

00:28:15.520 --> 00:28:16.519
it should do that thing.

00:28:16.519 --> 00:28:19.200
PROFESSOR: It should do the
thing it promises to do.

00:28:19.200 --> 00:28:21.650
AUDIENCE: It should abide by
all regulations and safety

00:28:21.650 --> 00:28:24.245
conditions so it doesn't
hurt you in the process.

00:28:24.245 --> 00:28:24.870
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:28:24.870 --> 00:28:25.703
It doesn't hurt you.

00:28:25.703 --> 00:28:27.414
It protects the user.

00:28:27.414 --> 00:28:29.289
AUDIENCE: Does that mean
you should design it

00:28:29.289 --> 00:28:31.939
in an honest way, as in not
steal the design from somebody?

00:28:31.939 --> 00:28:33.355
PROFESSOR: That's
a good question.

00:28:33.355 --> 00:28:34.980
Should you design it
in an honest ways,

00:28:34.980 --> 00:28:36.269
as in not steal the design?

00:28:36.269 --> 00:28:36.810
I don't know.

00:28:36.810 --> 00:28:37.726
We should ask Samsung.

00:28:40.495 --> 00:28:43.620
A little jab at that.

00:28:43.620 --> 00:28:44.496
It's a good question.

00:28:44.496 --> 00:28:46.620
AUDIENCE: I just don't know
what it's referring to.

00:28:46.620 --> 00:28:48.010
PROFESSOR: I don't either.

00:28:48.010 --> 00:28:49.970
I think we can actually find out
more information now about it.

00:28:49.970 --> 00:28:51.039
But it's a good question.

00:28:51.039 --> 00:28:52.330
What does it mean to be honest?

00:28:52.330 --> 00:28:53.720
It might mean that as well.

00:28:53.720 --> 00:28:57.830
It can mean a lot of things
about what its intended use is.

00:28:57.830 --> 00:28:59.620
When I use it, does
it do what it's

00:28:59.620 --> 00:29:03.078
supposed to do-- what
it promises to do?

00:29:03.078 --> 00:29:05.790
AUDIENCE: It can
also be adding more

00:29:05.790 --> 00:29:09.787
than it needs to be--
like making a gold hammer.

00:29:09.787 --> 00:29:10.745
PROFESSOR: Gold hammer.

00:29:10.745 --> 00:29:14.542
So that gold toothbrush
that we saw from Napoleon.

00:29:14.542 --> 00:29:17.091
It may not be an honest design.

00:29:17.091 --> 00:29:17.840
Maybe it's silver.

00:29:17.840 --> 00:29:20.460
Silver toothbrush.

00:29:20.460 --> 00:29:23.440
Can we think of an example
where this is not true?

00:29:23.440 --> 00:29:25.350
Where design is dishonest?

