AUDIENCE: Well, maybe not
a lot, but if you look back

00:31:34.103 --> 00:31:37.695
at older shows that were
predicting what the future was

00:31:37.695 --> 00:31:43.250
going to be like, they might
be spot on with the technology,

00:31:43.250 --> 00:31:46.050
but the aesthetics
of things-- we

00:31:46.050 --> 00:31:47.940
tend to have more rounded
corners on things.

00:31:47.940 --> 00:31:49.960
We don't like the
points as much anymore.

00:31:49.960 --> 00:31:52.840
Things like that, that people
hadn't even considered back

00:31:52.840 --> 00:31:56.850
then, are just taken for
granted now-- sort of.

00:31:56.850 --> 00:31:57.890
PROFESSOR: Interesting.

00:31:57.890 --> 00:31:59.348
AUDIENCE: Well, I
mean, good design

00:31:59.348 --> 00:32:01.252
can be determined
after the fact.

00:32:01.252 --> 00:32:02.984
Maybe when you
make it, you don't

00:32:02.984 --> 00:32:04.108
know if it's a good design.

00:32:04.108 --> 00:32:06.942
And then after
tastes change and you

00:32:06.942 --> 00:32:08.120
are 10 years down the road--

00:32:08.120 --> 00:32:09.340
PROFESSOR: You're able
to see if it's still

00:32:09.340 --> 00:32:11.550
a good, sustainable,
relevant design later on.

00:32:11.550 --> 00:32:13.640
Interesting.

00:32:13.640 --> 00:32:19.360
Good design is consequent
to the last detail.

00:32:19.360 --> 00:32:21.540
Who thinks it's true?

00:32:21.540 --> 00:32:23.330
Who thinks it's false?

00:32:23.330 --> 00:32:25.600
Who is unsure?

00:32:25.600 --> 00:32:28.370
Who did not vote?

00:32:28.370 --> 00:32:29.930
Let's try it again.

00:32:29.930 --> 00:32:33.550
Given your options, good
design is-- Let's clarify

00:32:33.550 --> 00:32:35.540
what it means.

00:32:35.540 --> 00:32:37.830
My mistake here.

00:32:37.830 --> 00:32:41.234
What does it mean to be
consequent to the last detail?

00:32:41.234 --> 00:32:44.276
AUDIENCE: Everything you
put in the design has

00:32:44.276 --> 00:32:45.182
the intended effect.

00:32:45.182 --> 00:32:47.140
PROFESSOR: Everything
you put in the design has

00:32:47.140 --> 00:32:47.780
the intended effect.

00:32:47.780 --> 00:32:48.280
Everything.

00:32:50.630 --> 00:32:54.440
If you were going to give
me a written report--

00:32:54.440 --> 00:32:58.390
a big one-- give me some
aspects of that report

00:32:58.390 --> 00:33:02.588
that you'd be concerned about.

00:33:02.588 --> 00:33:04.689
AUDIENCE: Whether or not
the content [INAUDIBLE] .

00:33:04.689 --> 00:33:05.480
PROFESSOR: Content.

00:33:05.480 --> 00:33:08.050
What else?

00:33:08.050 --> 00:33:08.930
AUDIENCE: Citations.

00:33:08.930 --> 00:33:09.805
PROFESSOR: Citations.

00:33:09.805 --> 00:33:10.490
What else?

00:33:10.490 --> 00:33:11.740
AUDIENCE: It's understandable.

00:33:11.740 --> 00:33:13.156
PROFESSOR: If it's
understandable.

00:33:13.156 --> 00:33:13.770
Comprehension.

00:33:13.770 --> 00:33:14.630
AUDIENCE: Format.

00:33:14.630 --> 00:33:15.660
PROFESSOR: Format.

00:33:15.660 --> 00:33:17.192
So the--

00:33:17.192 --> 00:33:18.120
AUDIENCE: Structure.

00:33:18.120 --> 00:33:19.161
PROFESSOR: The structure.

00:33:19.161 --> 00:33:19.704
What else?

00:33:19.704 --> 00:33:21.370
AUDIENCE: I was going
to say the format.

00:33:21.370 --> 00:33:22.430
PROFESSOR: Format.

00:33:22.430 --> 00:33:23.217
What else?

00:33:23.217 --> 00:33:24.050
AUDIENCE: Font size.

00:33:24.050 --> 00:33:26.260
PROFESSOR: The font size.

00:33:26.260 --> 00:33:27.620
And therefore, what else?

00:33:27.620 --> 00:33:28.480
AUDIENCE: The font.

00:33:28.480 --> 00:33:29.581
PROFESSOR: The font.

00:33:29.581 --> 00:33:30.080
Absolutely.

00:33:30.080 --> 00:33:32.474
What else?

00:33:32.474 --> 00:33:34.410
AUDIENCE: Is it too wordy?

00:33:34.410 --> 00:33:35.732
PROFESSOR: Length of words.

00:33:35.732 --> 00:33:37.190
AUDIENCE: The paper
it's on itself.

00:33:37.190 --> 00:33:38.520
PROFESSOR: The paper
it's on itself.

00:33:38.520 --> 00:33:39.020
Absolutely.

00:33:39.020 --> 00:33:39.897
What else then?

00:33:39.897 --> 00:33:45.260
AUDIENCE: Does it fulfil
the task and requirements?

00:33:45.260 --> 00:33:47.542
PROFESSOR: Does it fill
the task and requirements?

00:33:47.542 --> 00:33:48.625
We talked about the paper.

00:33:48.625 --> 00:33:50.276
I heard something else here.

00:33:50.276 --> 00:33:51.400
AUDIENCE: Color of the ink.

00:33:51.400 --> 00:33:52.441
PROFESSOR: Color the ink.

00:33:52.441 --> 00:33:53.150
Absolutely.

00:33:53.150 --> 00:33:54.371
Color of the ink.

00:33:54.371 --> 00:33:56.920
AUDIENCE: When you present the
paper-- like if it's bound.

00:33:56.920 --> 00:33:57.180
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:33:57.180 --> 00:33:57.750
If it's bound.

00:33:57.750 --> 00:33:58.416
If it's stapled.

00:33:58.416 --> 00:33:59.780
How it's bound.

00:33:59.780 --> 00:34:02.742
All these things are details.

00:34:02.742 --> 00:34:03.950
Do you think they all matter?

00:34:03.950 --> 00:34:04.894
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:34:04.894 --> 00:34:06.810
PROFESSOR: Who thinks
if you take a paper that

00:34:06.810 --> 00:34:08.665
has brilliant
content and a paper

00:34:08.665 --> 00:34:10.395
with the exact
same content-- two

00:34:10.395 --> 00:34:12.020
of them with the same
content-- and one

00:34:12.020 --> 00:34:15.241
is stapled in the corner and
one is bound beautifully--

00:34:15.241 --> 00:34:17.449
do you think that they will
affect your grade at all?

00:34:17.449 --> 00:34:21.161
Who thinks it will
not affect your grade?

00:34:21.161 --> 00:34:23.600
Who thinks it will
affect your grade?

00:34:23.600 --> 00:34:24.170
That's good.

00:34:24.170 --> 00:34:26.129
Statistics show that it
will affect your grade.

00:34:26.129 --> 00:34:28.669
Everyone who doesn't think that
it doesn't affect your grade,

00:34:28.669 --> 00:34:30.929
you should make sure that
your papers are well bound--

00:34:30.929 --> 00:34:33.489
because it looks to someone
else like you put more work

00:34:33.489 --> 00:34:35.360
and effort into it
and that you believe

00:34:35.360 --> 00:34:38.514
more sincerely in your product.

00:34:38.514 --> 00:34:40.972
AUDIENCE: A lot of that depends
on what the value system is

00:34:40.972 --> 00:34:43.084
that you're working on.

00:34:43.084 --> 00:34:44.584
If you don't actually
have the money

00:34:44.584 --> 00:34:47.044
or you don't want to spend
the money to bind that paper

00:34:47.044 --> 00:34:49.504
and you think that it's good
enough on its own then maybe

00:34:49.504 --> 00:34:51.472
the best design
isn't binding it.

00:34:51.472 --> 00:34:53.932
You might have a professor
who doesn't care.

00:34:53.932 --> 00:34:57.040
Given it's on average you
will score higher [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:57.040 --> 00:34:57.790
PROFESSOR: So yes.

00:34:57.790 --> 00:35:00.590
You have a specific case
where it doesn't matter.

00:35:00.590 --> 00:35:01.549
That's true.

00:35:01.549 --> 00:35:04.090
AUDIENCE: I think you're talking
about high school teachers--

00:35:04.090 --> 00:35:06.465
that probably doesn't apply--
but once you start going

00:35:06.465 --> 00:35:08.590
into college and you're
looking at the true content

00:35:08.590 --> 00:35:09.320
of the paper--

00:35:09.320 --> 00:35:10.600
PROFESSOR: You think it
applies in high school

00:35:10.600 --> 00:35:11.300
but not in college.

00:35:11.300 --> 00:35:12.716
AUDIENCE: I think it
applies less in college

00:35:12.716 --> 00:35:13.190
than it does in high school.

00:35:13.190 --> 00:35:15.500
PROFESSOR: I will tell
you this is not true.

00:35:15.500 --> 00:35:17.150
I will tell you from firsthand.

00:35:17.150 --> 00:35:20.230
And when I get a paper--
and I know this to be true--

00:35:20.230 --> 00:35:23.337
if anyone submits
their midterm report--

00:35:23.337 --> 00:35:25.170
their individual project--
and it is stapled

00:35:25.170 --> 00:35:28.030
in the upper left hand corner,
you will with 100% certainly

00:35:28.030 --> 00:35:31.210
be dropping the class
soon afterwards.

00:35:31.210 --> 00:35:33.374
I've seen it every
single semester.

00:35:33.374 --> 00:35:35.290
Every semester, I'll get
at least one person--

00:35:35.290 --> 00:35:36.850
and I'll say, please
do not do that--

00:35:36.850 --> 00:35:38.986
and they will give it to
me anyway bound like that.

00:35:38.986 --> 00:35:40.610
And I just suddenly
have to count to 10

00:35:40.610 --> 00:35:42.060
before they drop the class.

00:35:42.060 --> 00:35:44.354
AUDIENCE: But do you ask
them not to staple it?

00:35:44.354 --> 00:35:45.770
PROFESSOR: I say,
please don't use

00:35:45.770 --> 00:35:47.630
a staple in the upper
left hand corner.

00:35:47.630 --> 00:35:48.914
And they do it anyway.

00:35:48.914 --> 00:35:50.580
There's a high
correlation between this.

00:35:50.580 --> 00:35:53.530
And teachers, when you get
that beautifully bound thing,

00:35:53.530 --> 00:35:55.996
you think, wow, look
how cool this is.

00:35:55.996 --> 00:35:57.620
If you could sit in
those rooms, you'll

00:35:57.620 --> 00:35:58.780
think there is a difference.

00:35:58.780 --> 00:36:00.430
And of course, they will
read the content as well.

00:36:00.430 --> 00:36:02.700
It's not that it's going
to make up for bad content.

00:36:02.700 --> 00:36:04.870
But it shows a lot more
strength and structure.

00:36:04.870 --> 00:36:06.870
And their brain will start
focusing a little bit

00:36:06.870 --> 00:36:10.087
differently when they
review that paper.

00:36:10.087 --> 00:36:11.420
Consequently to the last detail.

00:36:11.420 --> 00:36:15.300
Who thinks that good design is
consequent to the last detail?

00:36:15.300 --> 00:36:18.110
Who thinks it is not?

00:36:18.110 --> 00:36:18.643
Why not?

00:36:18.643 --> 00:36:20.476
AUDIENCE: Well, I mean,
it's the same thing.

00:36:20.476 --> 00:36:21.975
It's just like, you
have to consider

00:36:21.975 --> 00:36:23.410
what the audience will do.

00:36:23.410 --> 00:36:25.619
You need to knowledge the
value of that extra detail.

00:36:25.619 --> 00:36:27.410
If they don't value
it, like if you're just

00:36:27.410 --> 00:36:30.011
trying to feed a lot of people
and they're just incredibly

00:36:30.011 --> 00:36:32.866
hungry-- if you are trying to
feed a starving population,

00:36:32.866 --> 00:36:34.657
they're not going to
care that you seasoned

00:36:34.657 --> 00:36:36.613
the food that you've
made exactly perfectly.

00:36:36.613 --> 00:36:38.080
They're going to care once
they get something to eat

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:39.070
and they get more of it.

00:36:39.070 --> 00:36:40.610
PROFESSOR: What if you
could season it perfectly?

00:36:40.610 --> 00:36:41.430
Would that be better design?

00:36:41.430 --> 00:36:41.893
AUDIENCE: Well,
that would be great,

00:36:41.893 --> 00:36:43.392
but that's not the
world we live in.

00:36:43.392 --> 00:36:45.140
We live in a world
with limitations

00:36:45.140 --> 00:36:45.765
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:36:45.765 --> 00:36:47.030
We do live with limitations.

00:36:47.030 --> 00:36:49.450
But the question I would
ask you to think about

00:36:49.450 --> 00:36:52.560
is when are those
limitations real

00:36:52.560 --> 00:36:55.820
and when do we impose them
on ourselves unnecessarily?

00:36:55.820 --> 00:37:00.730
When do we think, well, we can't
do this, instead of thinking,

00:37:00.730 --> 00:37:03.976
well, maybe we can't do this--
let's see if we can do it.

00:37:03.976 --> 00:37:05.850
You'll find a tremendous
amount of innovation

00:37:05.850 --> 00:37:11.940
happens when we resolve
the tension between what?

00:37:11.940 --> 00:37:12.950
From last class.

00:37:12.950 --> 00:37:15.254
AUDIENCE: From what we desire?

00:37:15.254 --> 00:37:15.920
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:37:15.920 --> 00:37:17.586
From what we desire
and what we require.

00:37:17.586 --> 00:37:19.580
If we can resolve
these tensions,

00:37:19.580 --> 00:37:22.020
that is where we get innovation.

00:37:22.020 --> 00:37:23.404
Absolutely.

00:37:23.404 --> 00:37:25.320
Good design is concerned
with the environment.

00:37:25.320 --> 00:37:26.070
What does it mean?

00:37:32.251 --> 00:37:36.745
AUDIENCE: Good design
doesn't neglect anything.

00:37:36.745 --> 00:37:37.370
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:37:37.370 --> 00:37:40.550
Good design isn't just sitting
in its own little vacuum.

00:37:40.550 --> 00:37:43.700
It works within a whole
system, a whole big context

00:37:43.700 --> 00:37:45.850
of things, whether it's
a physical environment,

00:37:45.850 --> 00:37:50.350
a social environment,
or, like the iPod player,

00:37:50.350 --> 00:37:52.780
works with the
iTunes Music Store.

00:37:52.780 --> 00:37:56.440
It connects to other things.

00:37:56.440 --> 00:37:59.860
Lastly, good design is as
little design as possible.

00:37:59.860 --> 00:38:02.850
What does that mean?

00:38:02.850 --> 00:38:07.260
AUDIENCE: I think
to use other things,

00:38:07.260 --> 00:38:12.343
like how Apple used
previous designs.

00:38:12.343 --> 00:38:15.170
So maybe they didn't have
to redesign that much.

00:38:15.170 --> 00:38:17.200
PROFESSOR: So she's
saying less design.

00:38:17.200 --> 00:38:18.280
Not as much redesign.

00:38:18.280 --> 00:38:19.867
What other interpretations
do we have?

00:38:19.867 --> 00:38:21.000
AUDIENCE: Keep it simple.

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:22.361
PROFESSOR: To keep it simple.

00:38:22.361 --> 00:38:22.860
What else?

00:38:25.906 --> 00:38:27.780
AUDIENCE: Going back to
the example of Apple,

00:38:27.780 --> 00:38:30.429
they try to limit the number
of buttons that you have.

00:38:30.429 --> 00:38:31.970
PROFESSOR: Try and
limit our buttons.

00:38:31.970 --> 00:38:32.469
Yes.

00:38:32.469 --> 00:38:34.008
AUDIENCE: And also
with the mouse.

00:38:34.008 --> 00:38:35.750
Let's use the Magic
Mouse for example.

00:38:35.750 --> 00:38:38.030
There is no button like
there are with other mice.

00:38:38.030 --> 00:38:39.071
There aren't two buttons.

00:38:39.071 --> 00:38:40.670
It's just one
click that you use.

00:38:40.670 --> 00:38:43.169
And it's very intuitive to
how you're going to use it.

00:38:43.169 --> 00:38:45.460
PROFESSOR: So a Magic Mouse
has no buttons on it at all

00:38:45.460 --> 00:38:48.259
and you can still click anyway.

00:38:48.259 --> 00:38:49.550
And it knows what you're doing.

00:38:49.550 --> 00:38:53.087
They're just trying to
reduce that user experience.

00:38:53.087 --> 00:38:54.795
But they had a lot
more complexity inside

00:38:54.795 --> 00:38:57.150
to figure out how
to make that work.

00:38:57.150 --> 00:38:58.522
What else?

00:38:58.522 --> 00:39:01.746
AUDIENCE: I think the
design is as little design

00:39:01.746 --> 00:39:04.474
as possible as in off
of previous designs,

00:39:04.474 --> 00:39:05.922
like going back to Dieter Rams.

00:39:05.922 --> 00:39:07.130
PROFESSOR: Dieter Rams' work.

00:39:07.130 --> 00:39:07.640
Absolutely.

00:39:07.640 --> 00:39:09.960
Where he's really trying
to get that functionalist--

00:39:09.960 --> 00:39:12.501
let's think about the functions
first and really build things

00:39:12.501 --> 00:39:14.780
around in the simplest most
streamlined, elegant way

00:39:14.780 --> 00:39:16.550
possible.

00:39:16.550 --> 00:39:18.075
I want to consider these steps.

00:39:18.075 --> 00:39:20.700
Part of your homework will be to
consider if these are all true

00:39:20.700 --> 00:39:23.080
and reflect on them and see
how they can be improved

00:39:23.080 --> 00:39:24.624
and which ones are missing.

00:39:24.624 --> 00:39:27.290
I bet you're going to be able to
think of ones that are missing.

00:39:31.130 --> 00:39:33.030
Design challenge.

00:39:33.030 --> 00:39:34.890
Are you ready?

00:39:34.890 --> 00:39:35.780
Are you ready?

00:39:35.780 --> 00:39:37.420
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:39:37.420 --> 00:39:40.000
PROFESSOR: I'll take that.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:40.647
Here we go.

00:39:40.647 --> 00:39:41.230
Are you ready?

00:39:45.400 --> 00:39:47.000
This is what you know.

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:47.790
The music stops.

00:39:47.790 --> 00:39:49.400
A man is dead.

00:39:49.400 --> 00:39:50.662
That's all you know.

00:39:50.662 --> 00:39:53.580
You need to solve what
happened and why did it happen.

00:39:53.580 --> 00:39:55.000
And I will answer questions.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:55.960
I will say, yes.

00:39:55.960 --> 00:39:56.990
Or I will say, no.

00:39:56.990 --> 00:40:00.220
Or I will say, Relevant.

00:40:00.220 --> 00:40:02.640
That's what you get.

00:40:02.640 --> 00:40:05.480
And we need to do this quickly.

00:40:05.480 --> 00:40:05.980
Go.

