00:51:30.030 --> 00:51:32.440
Because that may be wrong.

00:51:32.440 --> 00:51:36.470
Research results may be good but
the conclusions may be wrong.

00:51:36.470 --> 00:51:37.870
So here we had great research.

00:51:37.870 --> 00:51:39.320
The question was, did he
die of internal injuries.

00:51:39.320 --> 00:51:39.820
Yes.

00:51:39.820 --> 00:51:40.736
Did something hit him?

00:51:40.736 --> 00:51:41.260
Yes.

00:51:41.260 --> 00:51:42.340
What did we conclude?

00:51:42.340 --> 00:51:45.300
That something hit him--
that he was stationary.

00:51:45.300 --> 00:51:46.190
Easy to do.

00:51:46.190 --> 00:51:47.300
This is Fitts' Law.

00:51:47.300 --> 00:51:48.430
It's pretty cool.

00:51:48.430 --> 00:51:52.367
I won't bother
explaining it right now.

00:51:52.367 --> 00:51:53.200
It's so interesting.

00:51:53.200 --> 00:51:54.830
It's used a lot in computer
and human interaction.

00:51:54.830 --> 00:51:56.155
I'll give you the basic idea.

00:52:01.540 --> 00:52:05.600
This distance is D. And I
think, here in the formula,

00:52:05.600 --> 00:52:09.290
this is W, which really
talks about-- actually,

00:52:09.290 --> 00:52:12.240
that's Ws here and Ws here.

00:52:12.240 --> 00:52:14.640
It's a margin of
error, technically.

00:52:14.640 --> 00:52:16.520
But here it's a width.

00:52:16.520 --> 00:52:18.540
And what he would do
is he'd say, look,

00:52:18.540 --> 00:52:20.601
we can have people doing
something like tapping.

00:52:20.601 --> 00:52:21.100
Here.

00:52:21.100 --> 00:52:21.799
Here.

00:52:21.799 --> 00:52:22.590
As fast as you can.

00:52:27.760 --> 00:52:31.210
Now if I take those
lines and I change them.

00:52:31.210 --> 00:52:34.320
I'm going to make
them like this.

00:52:34.320 --> 00:52:35.610
So that's one.

00:52:35.610 --> 00:52:37.850
I do this.

00:52:37.850 --> 00:52:39.390
Faster.

00:52:39.390 --> 00:52:40.190
What if I do this?

00:52:48.180 --> 00:52:48.866
Pretty good.

00:52:48.866 --> 00:52:49.610
Pretty good.

00:52:49.610 --> 00:52:51.100
And so I'm pretty
good with that.

00:52:51.100 --> 00:52:52.220
But my speed changed.

00:52:52.220 --> 00:52:56.570
And if I wanted to go faster,
my accuracy would go down.

00:52:56.570 --> 00:52:58.810
So what can we
conclude from this?

00:52:58.810 --> 00:52:59.875
Lots of things.

00:52:59.875 --> 00:53:01.916
Somethings that are very
good and somethings that

00:53:01.916 --> 00:53:02.885
are incorrect.

00:53:02.885 --> 00:53:03.940
One conclusion.

00:53:03.940 --> 00:53:05.820
If I work on a computer
system that just

00:53:05.820 --> 00:53:08.070
has a keyboard and
no mice at all.

00:53:08.070 --> 00:53:12.430
And it's now 1985, 1986.

00:53:12.430 --> 00:53:15.570
Should I use a graphical
user interface or not?

00:53:15.570 --> 00:53:18.262
Well the incorrect conclusion
might be it will slow you down.

00:53:18.262 --> 00:53:20.220
Because every time you
move your hand over-- we

00:53:20.220 --> 00:53:21.110
can calculate it out.

00:53:21.110 --> 00:53:23.110
How long it's going to
take you for every action

00:53:23.110 --> 00:53:25.299
that requires you
to use a mouse.

00:53:25.299 --> 00:53:27.340
And so we don't want to
have people slowing down.

00:53:27.340 --> 00:53:30.760
We're going to keep everything
using keyboard commands.

00:53:30.760 --> 00:53:33.420
But it may not be true that
it's going to make you faster.

00:53:33.420 --> 00:53:37.189
That's an incorrect conclusion--
maybe given that same system.

00:53:37.189 --> 00:53:38.730
But maybe if you
redesign the system,

00:53:38.730 --> 00:53:40.000
it will actually become
a system that you

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:41.910
can use faster because
you can use the mouse

00:53:41.910 --> 00:53:44.096
to be able to do things
you couldn't do before.

00:53:44.096 --> 00:53:45.720
And the correct
conclusion that we draw

00:53:45.720 --> 00:53:48.739
is the right click
for a pop-up menu--

00:53:48.739 --> 00:53:51.280
you right click on something
and then the menu's right there.

00:53:51.280 --> 00:53:53.290
So now you've moved
your hand to the mouse.

00:53:53.290 --> 00:53:54.795
You move your mouse
to the target.

00:53:54.795 --> 00:53:56.020
And you right click on it.

00:53:56.020 --> 00:53:57.900
And now you have a
menu that's contextual,

00:53:57.900 --> 00:53:59.234
that's short and easy to get to.

00:53:59.234 --> 00:54:01.358
Instead of moving your
mouse all the way to the top

00:54:01.358 --> 00:54:03.990
to a big menu bar and having to
find your way through cascading

00:54:03.990 --> 00:54:05.740
menus.

00:54:05.740 --> 00:54:08.050
That is the correct use of it.

00:54:08.050 --> 00:54:10.790
Research results may be good
but conclusions may be wrong.

00:54:10.790 --> 00:54:13.600
So when you see a really good
research piece like this,

00:54:13.600 --> 00:54:18.630
understand that what you do
with that is really important.

00:54:18.630 --> 00:54:19.990
We design projects for people.

00:54:19.990 --> 00:54:22.730
People don't know
what they want often.

00:54:22.730 --> 00:54:25.560
I could say, do you want
to have a device that's

00:54:25.560 --> 00:54:28.645
this big and flat and has a
keyboard on it that's virtual

00:54:28.645 --> 00:54:29.610
and all the stuff.

00:54:29.610 --> 00:54:31.260
You might say, nah,
I don't want that.

00:54:31.260 --> 00:54:34.460
In fact, when the iPad
came out, the week

00:54:34.460 --> 00:54:37.510
beforehand or two weeks
before I had pre-ordered it

00:54:37.510 --> 00:54:40.230
because I had to be
really cool and wanted it.

00:54:40.230 --> 00:54:44.705
And my classmates were
saying, oh that's ridiculous.

00:54:44.705 --> 00:54:46.400
I said, why is it ridiculous?

00:54:46.400 --> 00:54:50.290
Well, it's like a bigger
iPhone and you don't need that.

00:54:50.290 --> 00:54:51.900
And I'm like I think
it's different.

00:54:51.900 --> 00:54:54.266
They said, no, it's
just a bigger iPhone.

00:54:54.266 --> 00:54:55.390
We're not going to get one.

00:54:55.390 --> 00:54:57.598
Well within a month, of
course, a whole bunch of them

00:54:57.598 --> 00:54:59.790
are ordering them because
they saw it was different.

00:54:59.790 --> 00:55:01.706
But if you asked them--
if you said, would you

00:55:01.706 --> 00:55:06.370
like to pay $600 or $800
for an object like this,

00:55:06.370 --> 00:55:08.430
they might have said, no.

00:55:08.430 --> 00:55:11.330
And then they never
would've made an iPad.

00:55:11.330 --> 00:55:13.720
It's very hard to ask
people what they want.

00:55:13.720 --> 00:55:17.450
And if they know what they want,
they often can't articulate it.

00:55:17.450 --> 00:55:20.670
They don't know what words
to use to convey the idea.

00:55:20.670 --> 00:55:22.506
So as a designer
when you research,

00:55:22.506 --> 00:55:24.880
how you ask questions, how
you interpret people's answers

00:55:24.880 --> 00:55:25.671
is really critical.

00:55:28.910 --> 00:55:33.675
