Not when you're doing something
completely radical and new

01:11:11.960 --> 01:11:13.585
and very different
and very innovative.

01:11:16.376 --> 01:11:18.792
AUDIENCE: I just wanted to
support his point a little bit.

01:11:18.792 --> 01:11:21.768
I don't think that
anyone who designs

01:11:21.768 --> 01:11:25.736
these really good products
sits down one day and realizes,

01:11:25.736 --> 01:11:28.712
given everything I know about
art, technology, society, etc,

01:11:28.712 --> 01:11:30.106
this is how it should be.

01:11:30.106 --> 01:11:31.355
PROFESSOR: You don't think so?

01:11:31.355 --> 01:11:32.450
AUDIENCE: No, I don't.

01:11:32.450 --> 01:11:33.570
PROFESSOR: If you were
to design something,

01:11:33.570 --> 01:11:35.992
you wouldn't think that it
was the amalgam of everything

01:11:35.992 --> 01:11:37.450
you've learned in
your life so far?

01:11:37.450 --> 01:11:38.222
AUDIENCE: No, no.

01:11:38.222 --> 01:11:41.122
It wouldn't just come at once.

01:11:41.122 --> 01:11:42.580
PROFESSOR: It may
not come at once.

01:11:42.580 --> 01:11:44.121
AUDIENCE: Unlike
the other examples--

01:11:44.121 --> 01:11:47.390
in the other examples, you
narrowed down the [INAUDIBLE]

01:11:47.390 --> 01:11:49.285
because you realized
this causes this.

01:11:49.285 --> 01:11:50.160
PROFESSOR: Oh, right.

01:11:50.160 --> 01:11:51.201
It is not a good example.

01:11:51.201 --> 01:11:51.860
Exactly.

01:11:51.860 --> 01:11:52.580
That is true.

01:11:52.580 --> 01:11:54.234
But it is the
synthesis of everything

01:11:54.234 --> 01:11:55.150
you've learned so far.

01:11:55.150 --> 01:11:55.480
Right?

01:11:55.480 --> 01:11:56.146
AUDIENCE: Right.

01:11:56.146 --> 01:12:00.480
But the process of getting
to the design that you get to

01:12:00.480 --> 01:12:01.459
is a meandering.

01:12:01.459 --> 01:12:02.250
PROFESSOR: Oh, yes.

01:12:02.250 --> 01:12:03.550
You may take a long time
to get to that design.

01:12:03.550 --> 01:12:04.000
Absolutely.

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:04.490
Yes.

01:12:04.490 --> 01:12:06.073
But it is the idea
that, if you-- I'll

01:12:06.073 --> 01:12:07.290
bring this slide up again.

01:12:10.720 --> 01:12:13.429
If you don't have a deep
understanding of people,

01:12:13.429 --> 01:12:15.720
you're not going to design
things really well for them.

01:12:15.720 --> 01:12:17.490
If you don't understand
how the technology works,

01:12:17.490 --> 01:12:19.573
you won't be able to make
something that's useful,

01:12:19.573 --> 01:12:21.450
that people enjoy
interacting with that

01:12:21.450 --> 01:12:22.910
takes advantage
of the technology.

01:12:22.910 --> 01:12:24.390
If you don't understand
about the culture

01:12:24.390 --> 01:12:25.630
it may be the wrong
time to introduce it

01:12:25.630 --> 01:12:26.421
to a certain place.

01:12:26.421 --> 01:12:30.180
If the iPad was launched in a
poor country where they could

01:12:30.180 --> 01:12:32.461
never afford it, then it
may not be very popular.

01:12:32.461 --> 01:12:34.460
Or a place where there
wasn't internet reception

01:12:34.460 --> 01:12:35.129
for some reason.

01:12:35.129 --> 01:12:37.670
Or if you don't understand about
how to manufacture something

01:12:37.670 --> 01:12:39.760
like that, then it
gets very clunky.

01:12:39.760 --> 01:12:41.790
If you don't understand
about art or design,

01:12:41.790 --> 01:12:44.300
how do you make something
that's aesthetically pleasing

01:12:44.300 --> 01:12:45.214
and sustainable?

01:12:45.214 --> 01:12:46.880
So that's why the
idea is to synthesize.

01:12:46.880 --> 01:12:47.580
And yes.

01:12:47.580 --> 01:12:49.620
It takes a long
time to get there.

01:12:49.620 --> 01:12:52.275
That's why creativity gets
better as you get older.

01:12:52.275 --> 01:12:55.660
The older you get, the
more creative you will get.

01:12:55.660 --> 01:12:57.160
You don't get worse
with creativity.

01:12:57.160 --> 01:12:58.617
It gets better.

01:12:58.617 --> 01:13:00.450
Because you know more
and you have more life

01:13:00.450 --> 01:13:03.930
experiences that
you can synthesize.

01:13:03.930 --> 01:13:05.030
Other questions?

01:13:05.030 --> 01:13:07.012
Or comments?

01:13:07.012 --> 01:13:08.428
AUDIENCE: I feel
like it goes back

01:13:08.428 --> 01:13:11.055
to the conversation we
had about intention.

01:13:11.055 --> 01:13:11.930
PROFESSOR: Intention.

01:13:11.930 --> 01:13:13.620
The idea of intention.

01:13:13.620 --> 01:13:15.860
AUDIENCE: -and what
you intended it to do.

01:13:15.860 --> 01:13:19.635
I feel like it does require
the deep understanding

01:13:19.635 --> 01:13:22.970
of certain things depending
on what your design is.

01:13:22.970 --> 01:13:25.155
But it's like what
you said, it can

01:13:25.155 --> 01:13:27.270
evolve into different
things and that

01:13:27.270 --> 01:13:32.895
might mean you will look for
more understanding of humans

01:13:32.895 --> 01:13:36.830
and manufacturing maybe later on
depending on where the design--

01:13:36.830 --> 01:13:38.520
PROFESSOR: So you'll
keep evolving that.

01:13:38.520 --> 01:13:39.020
Absolutely.

01:13:39.020 --> 01:13:40.895
You will definitely keep
evolving your ideas.

01:13:40.895 --> 01:13:42.190
Joel.

01:13:42.190 --> 01:13:44.315
PROFESSOR JOEL SCHINDALL:
Just to add a little bit,

01:13:44.315 --> 01:13:47.690
I hope you're not falling
into the school idea

01:13:47.690 --> 01:13:51.940
that these questions have
right and wrong answers.

01:13:51.940 --> 01:13:53.940
These are thought provoking.

01:13:53.940 --> 01:13:56.350
They're to get you
thinking about things.

01:13:56.350 --> 01:13:59.080
They're to challenge
your assumptions.

01:13:59.080 --> 01:14:02.120
Some of them are
absolutely ridiculous.

01:14:02.120 --> 01:14:05.280
But without looking at
that, it doesn't give you

01:14:05.280 --> 01:14:08.360
the perspective that
you're getting at.

01:14:08.360 --> 01:14:10.862
I think you've probably done
this in other sorts of classes

01:14:10.862 --> 01:14:12.570
but it's a different
type of perspective.

01:14:12.570 --> 01:14:14.750
And to get the most
value out of it

01:14:14.750 --> 01:14:17.750
you need to set aside--
by the way, the people who

01:14:17.750 --> 01:14:20.420
are answering, I also want
to really hand it to you.

01:14:20.420 --> 01:14:22.170
Put yourself out there.

01:14:22.170 --> 01:14:24.891
Throw it out even if it's--
there are not right and wrong

01:14:24.891 --> 01:14:25.390
answers.

01:14:25.390 --> 01:14:28.260
We need illustrations
of the wrong answers--

01:14:28.260 --> 01:14:31.850
we need illustrations
of the wide range

01:14:31.850 --> 01:14:34.990
that people come up
with answers about.

01:14:34.990 --> 01:14:37.210
I think if you're sitting
here in this class,

01:14:37.210 --> 01:14:40.780
the answers that other
people are giving

01:14:40.780 --> 01:14:44.820
are a demonstration of the
wide range of reactions

01:14:44.820 --> 01:14:47.449
that people have to the same
stimuli that you receive.

01:14:47.449 --> 01:14:49.740
And you'll receive a stimulus
and you'll say, oh, yeah,

01:14:49.740 --> 01:14:50.760
of course that's true.

01:14:50.760 --> 01:14:53.380
And someone else is going
to say, I object violently.

01:14:53.380 --> 01:14:55.990
Now that's worth knowing
because that person's

01:14:55.990 --> 01:14:57.780
giving an honest reaction.

01:14:57.780 --> 01:14:59.360
PROFESSOR: The
whole point of this

01:14:59.360 --> 01:15:01.477
is to provoke your thinking.

01:15:01.477 --> 01:15:02.935
To make you think
deeper about this

01:15:02.935 --> 01:15:04.600
and to set the
stage for what you

01:15:04.600 --> 01:15:06.660
will be doing over the
course of the semester.

01:15:06.660 --> 01:15:09.059
It is meant to
challenge the ideas.

01:15:09.059 --> 01:15:11.350
We ask a lot of questions
about Dieter Rams' principles

01:15:11.350 --> 01:15:13.980
and you'll be
reflecting on that.

01:15:13.980 --> 01:15:15.281
But these are ideas.

01:15:15.281 --> 01:15:17.530
And they're not meant to say
this is an equation where

01:15:17.530 --> 01:15:20.010
when you put something in you
get something out like this.

01:15:20.010 --> 01:15:22.160
It's not deterministic that way.

01:15:22.160 --> 01:15:24.560
Design is a very, very
complicated thing.

01:15:24.560 --> 01:15:26.810
That's why we talk about it
for many different aspects

01:15:26.810 --> 01:15:29.680
and different approaches to
get you to think differently.

01:15:29.680 --> 01:15:32.880
Because you'll be able to
soon become much better at it

01:15:32.880 --> 01:15:34.662
through that process.

01:15:34.662 --> 01:15:38.316
AUDIENCE: So I know that 2.009
is a very artificial setting

01:15:38.316 --> 01:15:39.816
because you're given
a theme and you

01:15:39.816 --> 01:15:42.027
have to design a product
based on that theme.

01:15:42.027 --> 01:15:45.960
But how do you think 2.009
and that process fits with--

01:15:45.960 --> 01:15:48.620
PROFESSOR: I don't know
a whole lot about 2.009.

01:15:48.620 --> 01:15:50.120
You said it's an
artificial setting.

01:15:50.120 --> 01:15:51.840
It's not that artificial.

01:15:51.840 --> 01:15:55.550
There are companies that have
innovation labs where they say,

01:15:55.550 --> 01:15:58.249
we do something with our
product in this space.

01:15:58.249 --> 01:15:59.790
Can you do something
with our product

01:15:59.790 --> 01:16:01.890
that takes advantage
of it somehow?

01:16:01.890 --> 01:16:04.160
And people have to figure
out, OK, what do I have.

01:16:04.160 --> 01:16:05.240
What are the resources?

01:16:05.240 --> 01:16:06.699
How much time do
I have to do this?

01:16:06.699 --> 01:16:08.198
Do I have an infinite
amount of time

01:16:08.198 --> 01:16:09.460
or a limited amount of time?

01:16:09.460 --> 01:16:11.899
And they do that same process,
just like you do in 2.009.

01:16:11.899 --> 01:16:14.440
PROFESSOR JOEL SCHINDALL: Blade,
let me comment on that also.

01:16:14.440 --> 01:16:17.020
Design takes place
at many, many levels.

01:16:17.020 --> 01:16:20.120
And sometimes, you just
have a group of flowers

01:16:20.120 --> 01:16:22.170
and you're trying to
make a floral design

01:16:22.170 --> 01:16:24.270
and you're very restricted
in what you can do,

01:16:24.270 --> 01:16:26.439
but there is a methodology,
there are rules.

01:16:26.439 --> 01:16:27.980
You can put the big
flowers-- I don't

01:16:27.980 --> 01:16:29.729
know how to do a good
one, so I better not

01:16:29.729 --> 01:16:31.155
give you examples of that.

01:16:31.155 --> 01:16:32.780
And on the other
hand, sometimes you're

01:16:32.780 --> 01:16:38.270
trying to do either a very
complex technical system

01:16:38.270 --> 01:16:41.170
or perhaps a complicated
political process.

01:16:41.170 --> 01:16:44.432
People design press briefings
for presidential candidates.

01:16:44.432 --> 01:16:45.140
It seems amazing.

01:16:45.140 --> 01:16:46.660
It seems they're
so bad it doesn't

01:16:46.660 --> 01:16:48.520
seem as if it could be designed.

01:16:48.520 --> 01:16:50.990
But it actually
is very carefully

01:16:50.990 --> 01:16:53.160
researched and designed.

01:16:53.160 --> 01:16:56.190
Now 2.009 places itself
kind of in the middle

01:16:56.190 --> 01:16:57.310
of the design space.

01:16:57.310 --> 01:17:00.840
It's more creative
than just figuring out

01:17:00.840 --> 01:17:03.160
how to assemble an erector set.

01:17:03.160 --> 01:17:06.460
And it does encourage you to
do some innovative thinking,

01:17:06.460 --> 01:17:11.380
but not as much-- we're trying
to go even one level higher

01:17:11.380 --> 01:17:13.570
and something that will
apply to everything you do

01:17:13.570 --> 01:17:15.790
and just, what we
call, design thinking.

01:17:15.790 --> 01:17:19.200
And it will help you
in 2.009, but it's not

01:17:19.200 --> 01:17:21.910
as specifically
applied to-- 2.009

01:17:21.910 --> 01:17:23.950
is a mechanical engineering
course for people

01:17:23.950 --> 01:17:26.940
who intend to grow up and
design mechanical things.

01:17:26.940 --> 01:17:29.560
And so it focuses on that.

01:17:29.560 --> 01:17:34.140
This is more for people who
intend to deal with life issues

01:17:34.140 --> 01:17:35.470
and come up with answers.

01:17:35.470 --> 01:17:37.969
PROFESSOR: Whenever you have
to do anything-- in my software

01:17:37.969 --> 01:17:39.369
company, I apply
these principles

01:17:39.369 --> 01:17:41.410
to everything we do-- the
ones I'm teaching you--

01:17:41.410 --> 01:17:44.880
to every aspect of it,
whether it's to hiring,

01:17:44.880 --> 01:17:47.760
to bring people on board, to
figure out what they're going

01:17:47.760 --> 01:17:50.310
to be doing the next week,
how we're going to communicate

01:17:50.310 --> 01:17:52.960
internally, how we're going
to communicate externally,

01:17:52.960 --> 01:17:56.220
which brings us to stakeholders.

01:17:56.220 --> 01:17:56.720
Cul Bono.

01:17:56.720 --> 01:17:57.900
What does it mean?

01:17:57.900 --> 01:17:59.860
Anyone know?

01:17:59.860 --> 01:18:00.820
Who benefits?

01:18:00.820 --> 01:18:01.970
Who benefits?

01:18:01.970 --> 01:18:03.840
So stakeholder.

01:18:03.840 --> 01:18:06.100
Well the definition I get
off the internet-- a person

01:18:06.100 --> 01:18:08.620
or group that has an investment
share interest in something.

01:18:08.620 --> 01:18:10.620
We talk about stakeholders
for your education--

01:18:10.620 --> 01:18:12.405
you or your family,
teachers, school.

01:18:12.405 --> 01:18:14.530
Who else could be a
stakeholder for your education?

01:18:14.530 --> 01:18:15.669
AUDIENCE: The community.

01:18:15.669 --> 01:18:16.710
PROFESSOR: The community.

01:18:16.710 --> 01:18:19.080
What community?

01:18:19.080 --> 01:18:21.657
AUDIENCE: The one that you
would benefit if you go--

01:18:21.657 --> 01:18:23.240
PROFESSOR: The
community that benefits

01:18:23.240 --> 01:18:24.731
when you go and do something.

01:18:24.731 --> 01:18:25.230
What else?

01:18:25.230 --> 01:18:26.136
AUDIENCE: Your employers.

01:18:26.136 --> 01:18:27.240
PROFESSOR: The employers.

01:18:27.240 --> 01:18:27.965
Yes.

01:18:27.965 --> 01:18:30.001
And actually
potential employers.

01:18:30.001 --> 01:18:30.500
Who else?

01:18:30.500 --> 01:18:31.570
AUDIENCE: The clients.

01:18:31.570 --> 01:18:33.421
PROFESSOR: Clients.

01:18:33.421 --> 01:18:35.670
When you're working at the
employer you have a client.

01:18:35.670 --> 01:18:38.160
Yes.

01:18:38.160 --> 01:18:40.702
AUDIENCE: I think the government
or the president in general.

01:18:40.702 --> 01:18:42.784
PROFESSOR: The government
or the president, or you

01:18:42.784 --> 01:18:43.830
could say the country.

01:18:43.830 --> 01:18:45.730
The country benefits.

01:18:45.730 --> 01:18:46.320
Absolutely.

01:18:46.320 --> 01:18:47.900
Who else?

01:18:47.900 --> 01:18:49.608
AUDIENCE: I don't know
if school includes

01:18:49.608 --> 01:18:51.314
this, but your classmates.

01:18:51.314 --> 01:18:52.230
PROFESSOR: Classmates.

01:18:52.230 --> 01:18:52.348
Sure.

01:18:52.348 --> 01:18:53.910
Tell me how your
classmates benefit.

01:18:53.910 --> 01:18:55.164
AUDIENCE: The more you
bring to the table,

01:18:55.164 --> 01:18:56.420
the more they're going to gain.

01:18:56.420 --> 01:18:57.086
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:18:57.086 --> 01:18:59.760
So when you have a certain
cohort in a business school,

01:18:59.760 --> 01:19:02.210
if there's people with
different experiences,

01:19:02.210 --> 01:19:05.020
they can bring new
ideas and formats.

01:19:05.020 --> 01:19:07.280
That's why we have
discussions like this

01:19:07.280 --> 01:19:08.874
at the beginning
of the lectures.

01:19:08.874 --> 01:19:11.040
You get more benefit because
you hear someone's idea

01:19:11.040 --> 01:19:12.470
that you hadn't thought
about before because they

01:19:12.470 --> 01:19:13.470
bring their perspective.

01:19:16.320 --> 01:19:17.310
Here's a quick sketch.

01:19:17.310 --> 01:19:19.700
Just a quick sketch
of how you might

01:19:19.700 --> 01:19:22.310
go about the process of
writing out the stakeholders.

01:19:22.310 --> 01:19:23.000
Flour Bakery.

01:19:23.000 --> 01:19:24.109
Who knows it?

01:19:24.109 --> 01:19:24.650
A lot of you.

01:19:24.650 --> 01:19:26.990
So this is a great
bakery, very close by.

01:19:26.990 --> 01:19:29.960
And its owner is Joanne
Chang, a friend of mine.

01:19:29.960 --> 01:19:32.454
And Joanne owns a bakery.

01:19:32.454 --> 01:19:34.370
So I'm going to say that
this is in the center

01:19:34.370 --> 01:19:36.900
and this is one of the
primary stakeholders.

01:19:36.900 --> 01:19:40.180
Workers would be another primary
stakeholder of the bakery

01:19:40.180 --> 01:19:44.090
because if the bakery's
selling product they get paid.

01:19:44.090 --> 01:19:47.780
There's a whole bunch of others,
of course, that we can fill in.

01:19:47.780 --> 01:19:52.460
Now we go from a secondary
one to the workers' banks.

01:19:52.460 --> 01:19:53.490
How do they benefit?

01:19:53.490 --> 01:19:55.710
Well, the Flour Bakery
gives the workers money.

01:19:55.710 --> 01:19:58.050
The money goes into the banks.

01:19:58.050 --> 01:19:59.600
So as we go through
that process,

01:19:59.600 --> 01:20:01.936
the bank begins to be able
to get more money into them,

01:20:01.936 --> 01:20:04.185
particularly a local bank,
perhaps, that's being used.

01:20:04.185 --> 01:20:05.560
And what's
interesting about this

01:20:05.560 --> 01:20:07.259
is there's a big
profound effect.

01:20:07.259 --> 01:20:08.800
What we're going to
do is we're going

01:20:08.800 --> 01:20:14.060
to have you do a quick
sketch for Flour Bakery.

01:20:14.060 --> 01:20:18.750
And what I want you to
do is to do that system

01:20:18.750 --> 01:20:20.910
with much more detail,
right now in class.

01:20:23.289 --> 01:20:24.830
And if you need to,
you can use lines

01:20:24.830 --> 01:20:26.350
to clarify what's happening.

01:20:26.350 --> 01:20:28.480
Someone pays someone,
like pay the workers,

01:20:28.480 --> 01:20:31.940
or the bank receives
cash as a result.

01:20:31.940 --> 01:20:35.890
I want you to work
in groups of three.

01:20:35.890 --> 01:20:38.300
If you have paper, please
draw this on paper.

01:20:38.300 --> 01:20:41.510
And then, we'll project
a few on the screen.

01:20:41.510 --> 01:20:44.760
So tidiness doesn't really count
as long as you can explain it.

01:20:44.760 --> 01:20:48.840
And you'll have about
10 minutes to do it.

01:20:48.840 --> 01:20:51.600
You can work with
any people you want.

01:20:51.600 --> 01:20:53.510
By now, the students
are trying to figure out

01:20:53.510 --> 01:20:55.430
how to map out a simple
stakeholder diagram.

01:20:55.430 --> 01:20:59.984
Now this is not a very full
or robust stakeholder diagram.

01:20:59.984 --> 01:21:01.650
It's just meant to
get everyone thinking

01:21:01.650 --> 01:21:04.470
about the system
that's involved.

01:21:04.470 --> 01:21:07.227
In a stakeholder analysis
that's done really well,

01:21:07.227 --> 01:21:09.310
you'd actually phase out
all the different levels.

01:21:09.310 --> 01:21:11.610
You'd think about all the
different stakeholders

01:21:11.610 --> 01:21:14.040
and where they lie in the
spectrum of value, too.

01:21:14.040 --> 01:21:16.650
